agency_desc: The national government agency that oversees Social Security and Medicare insurance programs.
service_description: Provides monthly payments to low-income seniors, age 65 or older, and persons of all ages with qualifying disabilities.
site_details:
? Online Portal: Visit website for information or to apply for benefits.
? Call Center: Call for information or to apply for benefits.
? In Person: Visit [https://secure.ssa.gov/ICON/main.jsp] to find local offices. -- Contact desired location to apply for benefits.
site_schedule:
○ Online Portal: Daily 24 hours
○ Call Center: Mon-Fri 8am-7pm (live help); automated information available 24 hours
○ Local office hours vary; see website for details.
site_eligibility: Only the Social Security Administration can determine a person's eligibility for SSI. The following should be considered general guidelines only: US citizens (and legal residents who meet certain criteria) -- With low income and limited resources (measured by set guidelines) -- Age 65 or older -OR- with a qualifying mental or physical disability

agency_desc: The national government agency that oversees Social Security and Medicare insurance programs.
service_description: Provides monthly income to workers at least 62 years old who have earned sufficient Social Security credits through paid and/or self-employment (generally requires at least 10 years of work). Eligible persons may choose when to start receiving benefits; generally the longer a person waits, the larger the monthly payments will be.
site_details:
? Online Portal: Visit website for information or to apply for benefits.
? Call Center: Call for information or to apply for benefits.
? In Person: Visit [https://secure.ssa.gov/ICON/main.jsp] to find local offices. -- Walk into desired location for more information or to apply.
site_schedule:
○ Online Portal: Daily 24 hours
○ Call Center: Mon-Fri 8am-7pm (live help); automated information available 24 hours
○ Local office hours vary; see website for details.
site_eligibility: US citizens and legal residents -- At least 61 years and 9 months old at time of application  (Monthly payments will increase the longer a person waits to apply.) -- With at least 40 Social Security credits (if born after 1929); which means a minimum of 10 years employment -- Beneficiaries may continue working and still receive benefits, but a portion may be withheld if they have not yet reached full retirement age.) -- Immediate dependents of a person receiving benefits may also be eligible for benefits.

agency_desc: The national government agency that oversees Social Security and Medicare insurance programs.
service_description: Issues Social Security numbers and cards to US citizens and legal residents. Social Security numbers are required to work in the United States and to receive some government benefits. Applying for a Social Security number or replacement card is free. Identifying documentation is required.
site_details:
? Online Portal: Visit website to set up an account and apply for a replacement card online.
? Call Center: Call for information.
? By Mail: Call for an application or download application online and mail with required documents (must be originals).
? In Person: Visit [https://secure.ssa.gov/ICON/main.jsp] to find local offices. -- Walk into desired location to apply for a card or request a replacement.
site_schedule:
○ Online Portal: Daily 24 hours
○ Call Center: Mon-Fri 8am-7pm (live help); automated information available 24 hours
○ Local office hours vary; see website for details.
site_eligibility: For a Social Security card: US citizens and legal residents -- For online services: Age 18 or older -- US citizens and legal residents -- With a US mailing address -- With a state-issued photo ID or driver license

agency_desc: The national government agency that oversees Social Security and Medicare insurance programs.
service_description: Provides monthly income for adults who have qualifying disabilities and who have accumulated the required number of credits through paid and/or self-employment, as well as for their children and dependent spouses or widows. Adults who have been disabled since childhood may also be eligible for SSDI through a parent's earnings record.
site_details:
? Online Portal: Visit website for information or to apply for benefits.
? Call Center: Call for information or to apply for benefits.
? In Person: Visit [https://secure.ssa.gov/ICON/main.jsp] to find local offices. -- Contact desired location to apply for benefits.
site_schedule:
○ Online Portal: Daily 24 hours
○ Call Center: Mon-Fri 8am-7pm (live help); automated information available 24 hours
○ Local office hours vary; see website for details.
site_eligibility: Only the Social Security Administration can determine a person's eligibility for SSDI. The following should be considered general guidelines only: US citizens or legal residents -- Diagnosed with a physical or mental condition that prevents or seriously interferes with the ability to work and has lasted, or is expected to last, at least one year or to result in death (some conditions automatically qualify) -- Earned the required number of Social Security credits through paid and/or self-employment (number varies by age) -OR- adults disabled before age 22 whose parent/s are receiving Social Security benefits or are deceased

agency_desc: The national government agency that oversees Social Security and Medicare insurance programs.
service_description: Provides a website where people can look up their local Social Security office location.
site_details: Visit website and input local zip code.

agency_desc: The national government agency that oversees Social Security and Medicare insurance programs.
service_description: Offers online access to any benefits disbursed to individuals by the Social Security Administration. Creating an online account allows individuals to track and verify annual earnings, estimate future benefits while working, access a proof of current benefits letter, and manage current benefits.
site_details:
? Online Portal: Visit www.socialsecurity.gov/myaccount to sign in or create an online account. -- For proof of current benefits: Select "Get a Benefit Verification Letter" and print document.
? Call Center: Call with questions or help in understanding how to request benefit verification letter online. 
? Note: Benefit Printouts are not available in-person/through local offices.
site_schedule:
○ Online Portal: Daily 24 hours
○ Call Center: Mon-Fri 8am-7pm (live help) -- Automated Information: Daily 24 hours
site_eligibility: Must be a direct recipient of Social Security, SSI, or SSDI benefits (not payees)

agency_desc: The national government agency that oversees Social Security and Medicare insurance programs.
service_description: Provides monthly income to the surviving spouse, ex-spouse, and/or dependents of deceased persons who earned enough Social Security credits (through paid and/or self-employment) to qualify. The amount paid is based on the deceased worker's accumulated work. Survivors must meet age, disability, and/or relationship criteria to begin receiving payments.
site_details:
? Call Center: Call to report a death or apply for benefits.
? In Person: Visit [https://secure.ssa.gov/ICON/main.jsp] to find local offices. -- Walk into desired location to report a death or apply for benefits.
? Note: Reporting deaths or applying for survivors benefits cannot be done online.
site_schedule:
○ Call Center: Mon-Fri 8am-7pm (live help) -- Automated Information: Daily 24 hours
○ Local office hours vary; see website for details.
site_eligibility: The following survivors of deceased persons who earned sufficient Social Security work credits may be eligible for survivors benefits; additional restrictions may apply: Widows/widowers age 60 and older, age 50 or older and disabled, or any age if caring for a child/stepchild of the deceased worker who is under age 16 or disabled -- Children under age 18, or age 18-19 if full-time high school students, or any age if severely disabled -- Parents who were dependent upon the deceased for at least half of their support -- Ex-spouses ages 60 and older (or 50 and disabled) who were married to the deceased for at least 10 years, or any age if caring for the deceased child -- must not be currently married unless remarriage occurred after age 60 (or 50 and disabled)

agency_desc: The national government agency that oversees Social Security and Medicare insurance programs.
service_description: Provides a one-time payment of $255 to an eligible surviving spouse living in the same household or dependent child upon the death of an individual who has worked long enough to be insured by Social Security.
site_details:
? Call Center: Call with questions, to report a death of a beneficiary, or to apply for benefit.
? In Person: Visit [https://secure.ssa.gov/ICON/main.jsp] to find local offices. -- Walk into desired location to report a death of a beneficiary or to apply for benefit. 
? Note: Lump-Sum Death Payment transactions cannot be done online.
site_schedule:
○ Call Center: Mon-Fri 8am-7pm (live help); automated information available daily 24 hours
○ Local office hours vary; see website for details.
site_eligibility: Surviving spouse of a deceased person who earned enough Social Security work credits -OR- If there is no surviving spouse, a dependent child who is eligible for benefits on the deceased person's record in the month of the death

agency_desc: The national government agency that oversees Social Security and Medicare insurance programs.
service_description: Provides a one-time payment of $255 to an eligible surviving spouse living in the same household or dependent child upon the death of an individual who has worked long enough to be insured by Social Security.
site_details:
? Call Center: Call with questions, to report a death of a beneficiary, or to apply for benefit.
? In Person: Visit [https://secure.ssa.gov/ICON/main.jsp] to find local offices. -- Walk into desired location to report a death of a beneficiary or to apply for benefit. 
? Note: Lump-Sum Death Payment transactions cannot be done online.
site_schedule:
○ Call Center: Mon-Fri 8am-7pm (live help); automated information available daily 24 hours
○ Local office hours vary; see website for details.
site_eligibility: Surviving spouse of a deceased person who earned enough Social Security work credits -OR- If there is no surviving spouse, a dependent child who is eligible for benefits on the deceased person's record in the month of the death

agency_desc: The national government agency that oversees Social Security and Medicare insurance programs.
site_name: MEDICARE HELPLINE - CENTERS FOR MEDICARE AND MEDICAID SERVICES
service_description: Answers questions, addresses concerns, and provides information to callers regarding all aspects of the Medicare program, including enrollment, billing, covered services, new card requests, and Medicare prescription drug plans. Provides information on Medicare-certified nursing homes, including summaries of state inspections, and can assist callers in locating physicians. The website also provides information and interactive tools to enroll in Medicare, request a new card, find physicians, and compare nursing homes.
site_details:
? Online: Visit website for information and interactive tools to enroll in Medicare, request a new card, find physicians, and compare nursing homes.  ? Phone: Call the helpline with questions about claims or other personal Medicare information. 
? Live Chat: Visit https://www.medicare.gov/talk-to-someone to chat with a representative online about Medicare related questions.

agency_desc: The national government agency that oversees Social Security and Medicare insurance programs.
service_description: A voluntary employment program that increases the choices and opportunities for eligible Social Security disability beneficiaries to obtain employment, vocational rehabilitation and other support services from public and private providers, employers and other organizations without endangering their disability benefits including health care coverage. Beneficiaries receive a Ticket which they may use to obtain services and jobs from state vocational rehabilitation agencies or organizations that have been designated as Employment Networks (EN) by the program.
site_details:
? Online Portal: Visit website for information or to enroll.
? Helpline: Call for information or to enroll.
site_schedule:
○ Online Portal: Daily 24 hours
○ Helpline: Mon-Fri 8am-8pm
